#--: IDEA: 'error' as a return type

Allow error as a return type to signify that calling this method/function will
always be a compile time error?

One use case could be when you are trying to hide the default constructor
('create') without having a replacement definition. You would then presumably
use a differently named constructor to create instances.

NO, don't do this. Redefine the default constructor to 'none'


#--: this type meta

type - (meta.type ?) when inside a type definition, this is a synonym for the
type name. Useful for self referencing in methods and fields. Instances of this
type have access to the *public* API of that instance only (no private
method/field access).

this - when inside a type definition, this is *this* instance currently running
the method. 'this' is of type 'type' but it is more specific. There is only
this 'this' :).  This instance of 'this' has access to the *full* API (public
and private methods/fields)

meta - when inside a type definition, 'meta' provides access to meta fields and
methods related to this type definition. The one true constructor created by
the compiler for this object is here as meta.create. meta.name has the fully
qualified name of this type (?). Other methods and fields?





